# trigger_error()

You can generate your own errors using `trigger_error()`. It's useful for custom error conditions.

```php
if ($age < 0) {
    trigger_error('Age cannot be negative', E_USER_WARNING);
}
```

Error types: `E_USER_ERROR`, `E_USER_WARNING`, `E_USER_NOTICE`.

`E_USER_ERROR` is fatal, while the others are non-fatal.

```php
<?php
function divide($a, $b) {
    if ($b == 0) {
        trigger_error('Division by zero', E_USER_ERROR);
        return false;
    }
    return $a / $b;
}

// This will cause a fatal error
echo divide(10, 0);
?>
```
